Some JSON-RPC implementations send `params: null` instead of `params: {}` for notifications with no meaningful payload (like `initialized`). The LSP spec defines `InitializedParams` as an empty interface `{}`, but `serde_json::from_value::<InitializedParams>(Value::Null)` returns `Err`, causing the bridge to reject a technically-valid notification.

Fix: Normalize `Value::Null` to `Value::Object(Default::default())` for the `initialized` arm (and any other notification arms with empty-param types) before deserialization. Add a test asserting that `json!(null)` is handled gracefully for `initialized`.

Example guard:
```rust
"initialized" => {
    let params = if params.is_null() { json!({}) } else { params };
    let p: InitializedParams = serde_json::from_value(params)
        .map_err(|e| format!("initialized params error: {e}"))?;
    server.initialized(p).await;
    Ok(Value::Null)
}
```

